segments.text: my master's degree, and then to get a PhD.
And I had to validate all of these courses that I took in 1937 and 38, 39.
Professor Hunt was ag eco teacher.
And I went to him and I said, Dr. Hunt, I need to validate your course.
And he reached over and gave me a book.
and said, take this.
And I read that book for three hours.
And there wasn't a thing in that book that I knew anything about.
So I took it back to him.
And I said, I didn't take this course.
He said, oh, what course did you take?
And I said, well, I took the course on cooperatives.
He said, oh, yes, I remember.
And he gave me a test on it.
And I had had contact with
one of the Grange field officers who went to Washington to lobby for the Granger.
That was the name of an organization, wasn't it?
Incidentally, he was from Granger.
And he took me to eat dinner one day in Austin and ordered steak mignon.
And that's the first time I ever saw one of them.
But I kept in touch with him, and I spent my time doing my work, and I got acquainted with Pakistanis.
With whom?
Pakistanis, East Pakistan.
Yes, sir.
And I was very familiar with one student, and he got to A&M three months after

the two months after the courses had started that meant in october something or other and i helped him catch up in genetics so we became friends and we were friends while he was there and the fact that i knew him as well as i did led me to want to go
to where he was, and I did in 1955, and spent nearly two years in Pakistan before I came back to start teaching genetics in 57.
All right, now, did you finish your PhD?
Right.
In what?
Animal breeding.
Animal breeding.
And where did you all live during those years in College Station?
We lived in the barracks that they had moved in.
Describe life for a veteran in those barracks.
Well, we had two bedrooms and four kids, and we got a bed rail, and we put bunk beds in one room,
for our four children, and my wife and I slept in the other.
And she got a job and worked while I was there.
After we'd been there, I didn't get enough on my GI to feed the family.
Now these were, you said the barracks, this was over at College View?
Right.
Do you remember what the rent was?
Because I don't know that.
I don't know that.
It wasn't very much.
Somebody asked me one time, well, can you live with four kids in College View?
And I said, well, you can if you needed to do it as best as I did.
But after I'd been there for a while, we saw Qazi quite often.
And he invited us to all of the Pakistani functions.
He got a telegram one day and came to our house at noon to eat lunch with us.
And when we sat down to the table, he handed me a telegram.
And this telegram said, your wife will arrive in New York City at such and such a time and said, attend her arrival.
And that time specified was four hours before he handed me that telegram.
Well, obviously he couldn't go to New York to meet her, so I suggested that Traveler's Aid would help us.
And I called the Traveler's Aid and asked them if they would take care of his wife.
And he talked to his wife, and all he could hear was boo-hoo-hoo-hoo-hoo.
And so we had to go and get a money order to send to Traveler's Aid to pay her transportation from New York to Houston.
And by the time we got those arrangements made and took off for Houston, we got to Houston at the same time his wife got to Houston.
And we took care of him for 18 months or more, his wife and daughter.
His daughter went to school in College Station.
Now, the campus in those days was crowded, wasn't it?
Not very compared with what it is now.
No, but compared with what it had been before World War II.
You bet.
And where did you all do your shopping, and where did the kids play?
Well...
the kids played with the other kids in the project house.
But our kids were all of school age except one.
And we had to have a neighbor to babysit the youngest one while the rest of them went to school and both of us went to work.
And where'd y'all shop?
Mostly at
a big grocery store right at the bend of the road up there in Bryan.
Oh, Wine Gardens.
Wine Gardens.
And we sometimes shopped at the store.
O'ers?
Yeah.
And were you all churchgoers in that era?
Yes, sir.
Where described the church?
We went to A&M, to the church that was there next to the campus.
Church Christ?
Yes, sir.
Who were the key teachers and advisors that helped you as a graduate student?
Bob Schrode comes to mind first.
Who?
Bob Schrode.
S-C-H-R-O?
No, S-H-R-O-D-E. S-H-R-O.
He was the chairman of my committee.
Okay.
Mr. Godby was on my committee.
And whenever they started setting up my program, he sat there just like I, he didn't know what was going on.
And finally he said, look here, he said, you people have set up for a Ph.D. so many hours.
Don't you think that's ridiculous?
Let's cut that back down.
And he eliminated 40 hours that they thought I ought to have to have a Ph.D. Now then, language, two languages are required.
And
There was a man that came over from Austin to teach German.
And I enrolled in this course and got my credit.
And somebody decided they weren't going to give him credit.
And I went to Dr. Morgan and said, look here, and told him what happened.
And he said, that is acceptable, and I'll write the dean that it is acceptable.
When I started Spanish, I got a Spanish book on agriculture.
And on the first page, I had to look up so many words.
And then on the second page, I had to look up so many words.
And when I got to page 25, I took the written test on Spanish and passed that Spanish.
But it didn't take long if you didn't devote your time to anything but studying Spanish.
to be able to read page 151, 52, so that I passed both of those that way.
Was O.D.
Butler a member of the department then?
He was head of the Animal Science Department.
All right.
Did you ever have any association with him as a graduate student?
Not particularly.
All right.
You finished your work then in 55?
I finished it Christmas of 1954.
And then what did you do next?
Well, A&M had sent a group of people to East Pakistan on September the 1st.
H.E.
Hampton of the agronomy department was the head of that group.
But there had been a Pakistani over here who was head of the, he was director of education in East Pakistan.
And he visited with me quite a bit because Qazi told him who I was.
And so after I finished whatever I had to do,
Then I was picked when somebody else didn't make the team.
Somebody was turned down, and McElroy was the name of the man that was going.
But they found out he had been in India, and they wouldn't have anybody that had been in India to come to Pakistan.
So they put me on as a consultant.
and assigned me to in East Pakistan.
When we got there, we lived in a house with a man that was single and he had part of the building and we had part of the building and we didn't move to .
We got there in January and it took me from January to April to get his house ready for us to move into.
And I got very well acquainted with Nero Amin.
He was at one time the high muckety muck in East Pakistan, but his party had been defeated in the last election.
But he was a fantastic individual and owned the house that we were to rent in Myman Singh.
Jane had an attack of appendicitis.
We took her over about midnight to the doctor there.
And the doctor said, well, she's got appendicitis.
And said, I don't recommend the DACA hospital.
You go to Mime and Sing.
There's a nun running a hospital in Mime and Sing.
So I put her on the train.
And we got to Mime and Sing about midnight.
went to the hospital and they bedded me down in one place and put Jane in another place.
They started to get her out to go to surgery and she said, look, I'm not going to surgery until I see my husband.
So they woke me up before Jane went for her operation and she never did go back to Miami, to DACA.
I went back to DACA and got the kids and brought them to Miami City.
And y'all were over in Pakistan how long?
Well, we got there in January of 1954, I guess.
We didn't stay quite two years.
We lacked about three months of being two years.
And the purpose of that project was to do what?
we were advisors to the college that we were assigned to.
And since my master's degree was in education, it was compatible for the place that I was to be assigned.
And we got to Miami and Sing in April, and we left a year and from April to August.
We left in August of the
57, no 56, to come home.
And Mr. Godby had already offered me the job, but I couldn't get home.
When I got home, it was already filled, and so I had to teach school one half year in Rosebud.
I looked around College Station, couldn't find anything.

enlarge my area until i got a job at rosebud all right and then after that half year you came back right i started teaching february 1957 as a professor of genetics genetics right and i'm not going to ask pay any other time what was that beginning salary well now it wasn't as much as i got when i was in pakistan
Mr. Godby started teaching at A&M when salaries were not very high, and he didn't consider, and I was underpaid the whole time that I was there.
What were your duties?
Teaching genetics.
No, but what courses and how many and so on?
Well, I taught only one course at A&M.
What was that?
Genetics 301.
And that was animal?
No, that was all.
Right.
Every bit and four.
seven or eight years, we had one genetics course, and anybody that had genetics on their plan had to take genetics.
And they finally hired a young man to help because my classes were so big.
And I proposed to him that instead of having one class for him and two for me, that we team teach it.

And so I gave him the last one-third of the course, which meant that I taught two-thirds of the class and then I was not, I was able to pursue other interests from then until the end of the school year.
And I taught the course in the summer the same way.
And normally how many were in your sections?
How big were they?
When I started teaching, there was an average of 19 in each class.
And whenever they hired him, my classes had gotten to be where there was at least 500 students each term.
I taught over 11,000 students at A&M.
Some of them one time, some of them two times, one three times that I know of, one four times.
What were your guidelines as a teacher?
How did you approach that task?
Well, to one extent or another, I taught the same course in genetics that I was taught when Dr. Humbert was head of the department.
But in the meantime, when we got into the molecular genetics, I had not any background at all
And I was thrilled when the young man came in and took over that third of the course.
I had taught it, but I had to teach it not as something I knew, but as something that I had learned to follow the sequence.
I don't think the course changed, but they had a better teacher that last third than I was.
And they thought, including the
animal husband, the department head, that he would come and show me up.

And when they started talking about genetics and so forth, they asked him what he thought about McNeil, and he said, look, I just came from the fountainhead of genetics, and genetics, McNeil's a mess.
best genetics teacher I've ever seen.
He got his PhD at Illinois.
I mean, at Cornell.
He'd gotten his undergraduate in Illinois.
What were the guidelines that you gave to your classes about how they should approach their work?
Well,
I don't exactly know.
There's one or two things that I had more than one student to tell me that they didn't know how to study and how to get along until they took their genetics course.
And I had one student by the name of Rick Perry.
And after he got into politics, I made a point to get in touch with him.
He and Kay Bailey Hutchinson came to Waco for a Lincoln Day dinner, and I stayed at the back.
And he recognized me.
I went to the back door as they were leaving, and he recognized me when he was as far away as that cabinet is over there.
And I said, well, Rick, he said, Dr. McNeil said you taught genetics and said your course was
the one that made me realize I didn't want to be a veterinarian.
And I've had contact with Rick quite a lot since then.
But you had, I'm sure you had some policies about people that cut class too often or went to sleep.
How did you handle those things?
Man missed class.
I always started today's lesson with where I left off.
Made a reference lesson.
to the last lesson.
And I had one student that came every other day, and when I was talking about reviewing for everybody, he was asking questions.
And I called him in.
I said, young man, I said, you ask questions when I don't want questions on that.
I've already taught that.
And I want you to know that his attendance was perfect the rest of the year.
And I checked my
students every day.
And the first day of class I said, look, no shoes, no shirt, no class.
I explained that at the beginning of the class.
What about going to sleep in class?
Well, I didn't have too many to go to sleep in class, I'll tell you that.
One guy went to sleep and he had on glasses.
dark glasses, and everybody got up and walked out, and he was still asleep.
I told one of the students to wake him up, and the student said, you wake him up, you put him to sleep.
But that weird sense of humor.
But I used a lot of illustrations that
were known to me.
I don't know.
Crossing over is something that's really important.
And when you have crossing over, you have a break in one chromosome and a break in another, and these swap and heal back this way.
And I told them about a cousin of mine whose hand was badly burned, and where there was burned space here and here,
that they grew together just like the chromosomes grow together after their ends are broken.
And they said, you have a lot of peculiar relatives one time.
But, I don't know.
Did you have, as a teacher, did you have anyone in your past that was kind of your model?
Not really.
I didn't admire Dr. Humbert too much.
Mr. Godby was my god, I'll tell you that.
And I guess I wrote my own.
Who were your closest associates and buddies as faculty members?
L.A. Maddox.
His office was on the end of the building.
M-A-D-D-U-X or O-X?
O-X.
He was an extension beef cattle man.
I was in animal industries.
And the toilet on that floor was through the same door that I went to my office.
And when he'd come down to go to the toilet and it was already occupied, well then we'd
talk together until he got an open space.
But L.A. and I were real good friends.

And when he told, when girls were admitted to the genetics class, he came by and said, well, there's one thing about it, says you're one of the few professors that have got to, don't have to change his language since girls are gonna be in your class.
And that was true.
You mentioned co-education.
Do you remember any discussion by you and your friends before women were admitted seriously?
Do you remember people talking about the possibility of women being admitted?
I can't say that I really I mean my own opinion was my own and since I knew it was contrary to Rutter's I didn't
communicate with many people about it.
Let's talk about the leadership of A&M.
The president when you joined the faculty was Dr. Morgan.
That's right.
What was your evaluation of him?
I thought he was great.
I don't know why he left, but I was sorry to see him go.
Did you hear him very often speak or see him much?
Not much contact with him.
The only time I had contact with him was when I went to talk to him about the German course that had been taught at A&M for all these years.
And they suddenly decided this won't do.
Because as I understand, in hindsight, he favored co-education and making the Corps voluntary.
And that that wasn't popular with the board at that point.
I can understand that.
I agree that that statement might very well be applicable.
When Mr. Rutter was first appointed, do you remember any initial impression you all had of him?
Well, he was not really highly regarded, and it was felt that he was
a political appointee, and that he had to learn on the job if he did anything.
Do you remember hearing any of his early speeches?
Well, I've heard a few of them, and I was told that the best speech he ever made was at Project House Reunion, the first one we had in 69.

And I don't know whether that, I mean, see, when I first started that work, I got in touch with a bunch of people, and whenever they had the reunion, I invited all of the old professors to come to the reunion and so forth.
And it was former faculty members who left there saying that Rudder made the best speech I ever heard him make at the project house.
And they told me in the Association of Former Students that Project House Reunion had more cohesion and so forth than any other group, including any core people, than did anybody on the campus.
Why do you think the Project House graduates had that?
because they had very little regard for A&M.
They did not have the loyalty for A&M that the other students did because they'd been discriminated and had such a hard time getting through school.
That's the reason.
Of course, whenever they built the project houses over there and put students in them,
they were more readily accepted than they had been when they were living in Navasota and Bryan and so forth.
Incidentally, my mother was a project house housekeeper for four years at A&M.
Please describe that.
They had a McClendon County house and a good many boys not

all but there was some boys from Moody and I just don't really know I think Russell probably invited her and daddy was out of a job so Russell asked her if she'd be a project house homemaker and she was she had the McLennan County house one year and it disbanded and then she had the
Erath County House at 208 North Houston for three or four years.
And they came over there from Huntsville and asked Russell about getting somebody to go to Sam Houston as the room, the matron for the band house at Huntsville, and she was there a couple of years.
All right, during that four years, she was the...
And what would be house mother?
Is that what they were called for the project houses?
Yes, sir.
Do you remember what her compensation was?
A dollar a student per month.
But she had 31 students in a bigger house.
And her duties were what?
Well, her duty was to purchase, prepare, and set the tables.
And they had somebody hired to do the dishwashing.
Because I don't know of any project house anywhere that had the students doing the dishwashing.
Did she have to keep the house, to clean the house, or anything like that?
Each student was responsible for their own.
They had a manager for each house.
And it was his responsibility to do the buying and to make sure that the boys kept their room clean and so forth.
How did she feel about the way the project house students respected her, treated her?
Well, she was treated very well.
The students respected and I'd say loved their house mother.
I only knew of one case where the students
were down on the house by then, and they moved out.
Do you think she was proud to have that association?
Yes, she was.
I want you to know that when you're 55 years old, as my daddy was, there wasn't a terrific demand in those Depression days.
And when she was living in Huntsville, my daddy worked from 7 until 7.
every night at a filling station for a dollar.
Now, she was the project house mother for when, what period?
About the first year.
She ended in about the first year of the World War II.
Oh, so from about 36 to 41, something like that?
No, then she was from 37, perhaps.
30, okay.
So right after you graduated from A&M?
It was maybe a year and a part of it, some, after I graduated.
Okay.
Describe some, when you were on the A&M faculty, describe some of your extracurricular activities with the students.
Well, I was advisor to the Alpha Zeta, and I was advisor to 10 freshmen in agriculture, and I was advisor to the Young Republicans, and I was advisor to another club.
I don't remember.
Were you involved with the judging teams?
No, not involved with them.
Describe Alpha Zeta and its work.
Well, Alpha Zeta is a national...
Agricultural Students Organization.
And the students select somebody from the School of Agriculture to be the advisor.
And the first year you're just a common, the second year you become junior advisor, and the third year you become the head advisor.
And so I spent three years as agricultural advisor for the agricultural Alpha Zeta.
Do you remember some of those youngsters with pride?
Oh, you bet.
Among them was Fred McClure.
Did he?
He was in Alpha Z.
Make believe that I didn't know Fred McClure.
Describe him as a student.
Well, I didn't have him as a student.
No, describe him as a young man.
He was a leader in whatever he took part in.
What made him a leader?
Well, one thing.
He had the right kind of personality, and he was willing to take charge of something when something needed to be done.
And he was president of the student body.
Did he have a good speaking ability?
Great.
He made the speech at the Future Farmer Banquet the year before he came to A&M.
And he did not have any contact with me as a teacher, but my only contact was through Republican politics in Alphazade.
What about as a sense of humor?
Did he have a sense of humor?
I don't really remember that.
Oh, it was superb.
Great, great, great sense of humor.
I had a student write on the bottom of his opinionaire page, you sure do have a weird S-I-N-C-E of humor.
And I nearly fell out of my chair when I read that.
That's good.
That's a good Aggie story.
Yeah, it is.
That's a good Aggie story.
When you were a faculty member, did the students ever try to play any pranks?
Share some of those.
Well, my class was strict one time.
I guess I was the only professor that was strict.
Was this during coeducational days?
No.
These were all male?
Yeah.
In the mechanical engineering building, petroleum engineering building, there was two doors in the room and there was a desk behind these two doors and the board was here.
And
After quiz A, two medical students came to me and said, we didn't study for quiz A and we both made poor grades on quiz A.
And said, we want to take a makeup.
And I said, look, if you've taken that quiz, that goes in the grade sheet.
They said, look, we'll take you to Houston and
take you to a ball game down there and give you plenty to drink and then we'll go out to this outstanding house out there, fish house out there, and we'll buy you the best dinner they've got.
I said, I'm not interested.
But it did make them known to me.
And after
a few, oh, maybe two months, I'd pass out exercise sheets.

If they could work those exercise sheets that I prepared for them, and I'd place them on the front desk, and people would come by and pick them up and go home and work them, and that prepared them for the test.
And one day, one of the students came to get his exercise sheet, but instead of going back to his
seat, he went out the door back of me.
And I was halfway through the quiz when I had my back seat turned to the class, writing on the board, and I heard clap, clap, clap, clap, about four steps or five, and the noise stopped.
And I turned around and I didn't say anything.
But I looked up at this student's seat and he wasn't in it.
So I told the student that was his roommate to tell so-and-so to come see me.
And I told the class that
I wasn't going to give any grades on the exam until I found out who was the guilty party.
And so he didn't come, and he didn't come, and finally I told his roommate to have him come see me, and he didn't come.
And finally I caught him going out of place, and I said, you come see me today.
And he came in and he said he was determined not to admit anything.
And I said to him, I said, well, young man, I hold your career in my hand.
You're a medical student.
And if your major professor, Dr. Gravitt, ever finds out that you streak my class, your future's not very bright.
And he said, I was still determined not to say anything.
And I put him down in front of me and I said, well, said the man that streaked my class hat on a red jockey strap.
He said, no sir, it was a maroon jockey strap.
And I said, well, now you understand that you've done something that has really gonna cost you and your career.
Dr. Gravitt won't stand for this.
But I didn't report him to Dr. Gravitt.
But somebody did because Gravitt never let him go to medical school.
He finally went to what is this other thing?
It's osteopath school.
And both he and his friend got degrees at some osteopath college.
And one of them was practicing in Conroe.
And I was going to Conroe frequently because they had a club over there.
So when I got ready to retire, I went to his friend in Conroe, and I said, look, I want to send an invitation to so-and-so to come to my graduation dinner.
And he told me where he was, and I sent the letter to this guy that was in the Army in Illinois, and he replied to it.
He had a little different scenario than I had because he didn't see it exactly like I did, but it was really an interesting letter and I have got that in my memoir.
I think that answers your question, I think.
What about some other tricks or pranks the students attempted?
You know, I don't remember any other particular ones.
Nobody wrote anything on the board before you got to class?
No, sir, I don't remember that.
Did any student ever come by and try to bribe you?
I think these two boys were the only ones that ever really tried to bribe me.
Did anybody try to high pressure you about a grade?
Some politician?
How did they do that?
Well,
I gave two sets of quizzes to every class.
And the answers on this row and the answers on this row were different.
And whenever somebody turned in a paper on this row with answers all on this row, they didn't get a grade.
And I had one or two people to come in and complain about that.
It didn't do them any good, but
I had a little girl come in to complain that she would have done anything I asked of her.
But I knew better than to ask of her.
But that's an impression that I had.
Did any politician or university administrator try to influence your grades ever?
Ever.
No, never.
And I only got one bad note.
I turned in my grades at 5 o'clock, and they should have been in at 1 o'clock, and I got a letter of reply by endorsement.
And I probably did, but my secretary had misinformed me as to when they had to be in.
So I wrote a letter of reply by endorsement.
You mentioned you were active with the young Republicans.
Describe your activity in the community and on the campus as a leader of the local Republican party.
Well, when I first got there and started teaching in 57, I went to a,
precinct meeting just because I wanted to find out what was going on.
It was at Phil Good's house.
I know you know that name.
And I found out that all of the Republicans that were active there were members of the John Birch Society.
And I did not
I did not want to make my membership in the Republican Party dependent upon the John Birch Society.
So I did not affiliate with the John Birch faction.
And I would have my friends write in my name for precinct chairman.
I never tried to put my name on the ticket.
But my friends would write in my name that I'd get enough votes to be precinct chairman and I'd go to the county chairman and we'd elect delegates to the state.
But I didn't dare go to a state Republican convention until 1966.
Why not?
I thought there's too much involved.
Did you feel that it was inappropriate for a faculty member to do that?
It's inappropriate for Republican members.
Oh, you mean...
Yes, I do.
With the Democratic majority.
George Raper in the Postal Department was Democratic chairman for years, but they didn't want anybody on the faculty to be Republican.
And I think I told you that when I was elected county chairman that the secretary of the school board, Cherry,
asked me to come see him.
And I conducted the election for the Brazos County party.
And after Clements was elected, he called me and said it wouldn't be necessary for me to come see him.
But I felt very strongly that Republicans were not
They were not tolerated.
Did any student ever say anything about your being politically active?
No.
Did anybody else anywhere near the university administration ever say anything?
Never said anything.
You see, there's an old man that was county chairman.
And then he got crossways somehow with somebody I don't really know.
And I don't even remember his name.
But he had a fuss with somebody and resigned.
And I got all the precinct chairman together and only one person voted against me.
And that was a woman who thought she was a big Republican, but
She really didn't know.
She said in the thing, well, you don't invite the young people enough.
And I took Gay's son and two or three other people to state conventions with me to give them, you know, Gordon Gay's young son.
And to one extent or another, I invited their participation.
When Bush was there in 70, I had, I thought, an extremely good politician.
And I introduced him to George Bush and recommended him as a staff member in 1970 when he was on the campus.
And he interviewed this young man and offered him a job.
Well, whenever this young man told
the people that he had been sort of working for while he was in school, that he had been offered this.
They said, well, we'll give you the same thing George Bush does.
And he's now president of the Agricultural Teachers Insurance Company.
And Marcus Hill and I have been real close ever since then.
What's his name?
Marcus Hill.
M-A-R-C-U-S. H-I-L-L. Marcus Hill.
And about several years ago, he invited Jane and I to come to one of their board meetings.
